The board of Ecobank Transnational Incorporated (ETI) Plc has proposed the payment of a dividend of $0.16 cents per share, amounting to a total amount of $40 million for the financial year ended December 31, 2021. The pan Africa financial institution stated this in a notice on the Nigerian Exchange Limited yesterday. Ecobank Group reported gross earnings up by 13 per cent to N 953.00 billion, while revenue rose by 11 per cent to N 712.9 billion in 2021 Profit before tax and goodwill impairment up 52 per cent to N 195.7 billion, profit before tax stood at N 195.7 billion in 2021, while profit after tax went up by 324 per cent to N143.1 billion. The bank’s total assets rose by 11 per cent to N 11.560 trillion, loans and advances to customers increased by 10 per cent to N 4.066 trillion, while deposits from customers up 13 per cent to N 8.283 trillion. Also, total equity appreciated by 11 per cent at N 902.9 billion in 2021. Recently, the group CEO, Ecobank, Ade Ayeyemi in a statement said: “we reported strong results, reflecting the continued diligence of Ecobankers in putting our customers first and ensuring that we meet their respective needs. “These results also demonstrate the hard work invested in driving efficiency in all our businesses in line with our deliberate focus on driving down our cost-to serve, sustain improvement in the quality of our credit portfolio, and strengthen liquidity and capital buffers.” “We have boosted the firm’s liquidity profile, thanks to growing customer deposits fueled by an acceleration in digital channel adoption, partnerships with Fintechs, Telcos, and businesses in the Payments Ecosystem,” Ayeyemi added. “During the third quarter, Arise B.V., a major institutional shareholder of ETI made a $75 million Additional Tier 1 (AT1) investment in the firm. onto the $350 million Tier two Sustainability Note ETI successfully issued to investors in June. The AT1 further improves our Tier one capital and double leverage ratio and demonstrates stakeholder confidence in our strategy and business prospects.” “Finally, we continue to invest in new digital and mobile capabilities to enhance customer experience, alongside the investments we are making in our people, processes, and controls, to ensure the continued resilience of our business and service delivery to our clients. I am deeply grateful to all our customers and the Ecobank team for the remarkable job,” Ayeyemi added. 